    <!-- Tickets and showtimes -->
    <section id="tickets" class="section">
      <h2>Tickets and showtimes</h2>
      <p>
        This section explains where to buy tickets for the best value, plus
        suggested showtimes and backup options for O, Mad Apple, and the Sphere.
      </p>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">O by Cirque du Soleil (Bellagio)</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>
            Where to buy:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Cirque du Soleil official site for O</li>
            <li>Bellagio entertainment section</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="small">
            Cirque offers a best price guarantee for its Vegas resident shows when you
            buy directly, which usually beats third party sites once fees are included.
          </p>
          <h3>Typical schedule</h3>
          <p>
            O usually runs Wednesday through Sunday with two showtimes per night:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Early show around 6:30 pm</li>
            <li>Late show around 9:00 pm</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Best times for this trip</h3>
          <p>
            Early show flow:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Light but special dinner around 4:30 to 5:00 pm</li>
            <li>Walk straight to the theatre for a 6:30 show</li>
            <li>Optional wine or short walk around Bellagio after</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Late show flow:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Relaxed dinner around 6:00 pm with full wine and dessert</li>
            <li>O at 9:00 pm to end the night</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Seat advice</h3>
          <p class="small">
            Aim for the middle sections, a bit back from the stage. The very front
            can be too close to appreciate the full water stage, while the mid bowl
            gives the most balanced view.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">Mad Apple by Cirque du Soleil (New York New York)</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>
            Where to buy:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Cirque du Soleil official site, Mad Apple page</li>
            <li>New York New York entertainment page</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Typical schedule</h3>
          <p>
            Mad Apple usually plays:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Most nights between Tuesday and Saturday</li>
            <li>Two showtimes: about 7:00 pm and 9:30 pm</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Best times for this trip</h3>
          <p>
            Early show option:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Mad Apple at 7:00 pm</li>
            <li>Sit down happy hour or small dinner at 5:00 pm</li>
            <li>Free choice afterward if they want more drinks or a walk</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Late show option:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Happy hour and wine around 7:00 pm</li>
            <li>Mad Apple at 9:30 pm as the high energy cap to the night</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Seat advice</h3>
          <p class="small">
            The theatre is built around a central stage and bar. Mid theatre seats,
            not too far to one side, give the best look at both the stage and the
            overall staging. Front tables feel immersive but can be very close to the action.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">Sphere ‚Äì Postcard from Earth</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>
            Where to buy:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Sphere official website, which routes into Ticketmaster for Postcard from Earth</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="small">
            Buying direct gives you real time seat maps, reliable barcodes, and any
            official promotions. Avoid random resale listings unless there is no other choice.
          </p>
          <h3>Typical daily time options</h3>
          <p>
            The Sphere commonly offers:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Afternoon showtimes</li>
            <li>Early evening showtimes (for example 7:00 pm)</li>
            <li>Later evening showtimes</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Best times for this trip</h3>
          <p>
            Recommended for this plan:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Early evening around 7:00 pm after a wine focused stop at Wally‚Äôs</li>
            <li>Or early afternoon around 4:00 pm if you want a long, drawn out evening later</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Seat advice</h3>
          <p class="small">
            Choose mid bowl seats, not the absolute front row. You want your eyes to
            be able to scan the full screen comfortably. Very high back rows are cheaper
            but feel more distant. The most expensive immersive seats are not necessary
            unless you want every possible effect.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">Getting value and avoiding overpaying</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Use official sites first: Cirque or hotel sites for Cirque, Sphere site for Sphere.</li>
            <li>Check Vegas.com only for last minute deals on less full nights, if you are flexible on seats.</li>
            <li>Same day discount booths are fine for some shows, but not ideal for headline shows you care about.</li>
            <li>Watch for extra fees. A small discount on base price can vanish once fees are added.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Brunch and dining -->
    <section id="brunch" class="section">
      <h2>Brunch, Mon Ami Gabi, and backups</h2>
      <p>
        This section focuses on the farewell brunch plus backup options, table strategy,
        and what to order for a wine loving pair.
      </p>

      <div class="columns">
        <div class="panel">
          <h3>Mon Ami Gabi farewell brunch</h3>
          <p>
            French bistro at Paris Las Vegas, directly facing the Bellagio fountains.
            Ideal time for their schedule is about 10:00 am on departure day.
          </p>
          <h3>How to book</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Book a 10:00 am reservation for the departure morning through OpenTable or the Paris site.</li>
            <li>In the notes, mention that this is a mother daughter farewell brunch and that you would love outdoor seating with a fountain view if possible.</li>
            <li>Arrive 10 to 15 minutes early and politely ask the host for a patio table near the rail facing Bellagio.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Best tables to request</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Patio tables, near the front rail.</li>
            <li>Use words like ‚ÄúStrip view‚Äù and ‚ÄúBellagio fountains‚Äù when asking.</li>
            <li>If patio has a wait, ask about inside window tables facing the Strip as a backup.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>What to order</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>French onion soup to share.</li>
            <li>Steak frites or steak and eggs for a savory main.</li>
            <li>Eggs Benedict or smoked salmon Benedict for a classic brunch plate.</li>
            <li>Brioche French toast or crepes as a sweet dish to share between them.</li>
            <li>Pastry basket if they want a drawn out coffee and conversation moment.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Drinks that fit their style</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Chilled Sancerre or French Chardonnay for wine lovers.</li>
            <li>Mimosas if they want ‚Äúclassic brunch.‚Äù</li>
            <li>Kir Royale or French 75 for a more elegant, celebratory drink.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="panel">
          <h3>Backup brunch options</h3>
          <p>
            If Mon Ami Gabi is fully booked or weather makes the patio less fun, these
            are excellent backups that still feel special.
          </p>

          <h3>Sadelle‚Äôs at Bellagio</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Overlooks the Bellagio Conservatory.</li>
            <li>Brunch style menu with bagel towers, French toast, and brunch cocktails.</li>
            <li>Ask for a table by the windows facing the Conservatory.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Bouchon at the Venetian</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Thomas Keller French bistro, often rated among the best brunches in town.</li>
            <li>Crab Benedict, pastries, and very good wine list.</li>
            <li>Request patio or window seating overlooking the quiet courtyard.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>More casual backup</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Poolside cafe or a lighter brunch spot if they are more focused on the flight than a big meal.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Spa -->
    <section id="spa" class="section">
      <h2>Spa services and discounts</h2>
      <p>
        The idea here is good quality relaxation without the steepest Strip spa prices.
        Prices and promos change constantly, but these patterns are reliable.
      </p>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">Realistic spa choices with better value</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <h3>The Spa at the Linq</h3>
          <p>
            Often one of the better deals on the Strip. Look for weekday massage or facial
            promotions on Vegas deal sites. Facilities are modern and simple, good for a
            practical reset.
          </p>

          <h3>Sahara Las Vegas spa</h3>
          <p>
            Frequently offers weekday or off peak specials for massage and body treatments.
            Good if they want a more modern feel without luxury pricing.
          </p>

          <h3>Treasure Island spa</h3>
          <p>
            A more affordable Strip spa that still has proper locker rooms and relaxation areas.
          </p>

          <h3>JW Marriott Spa Aquae (off Strip)</h3>
          <p>
            Off Strip but known for its hydrotherapy pools and seasonal specials. A great choice
            if they want a quiet, resort like spa day away from the casino environment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-header">
          <span class="label">How to hunt for discounts without wasting time</span>
          <span class="chevron">‚ñæ</span>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Check Vegas deal sites for ‚Äúspa day,‚Äù ‚Äúmassage,‚Äù and ‚Äúfacial‚Äù a week or two before the trip.</li>
            <li>Search specifically for Linq, Sahara, Treasure Island, and off Strip resorts like JW Marriott.</li>
            <li>Check resort websites directly for weekday or locals style promotions.</li>
            <li>If they only want sauna and hot tub, ask about a ‚Äúspa day pass‚Äù at high end properties. Sometimes a facility pass is cheaper than a treatment.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Neon Museum and maps -->
    <section id="neon" class="section">
      <h2>Neon Museum and how it fits</h2>
      <p>
        The Neon Museum is an outdoor collection of classic Las Vegas signs. It pairs perfectly
        with time in the Arts District and Old Vegas.
      </p>

      <h3>Location</h3>
      <p>
        Address: 770 Las Vegas Boulevard North.
      </p>
      <p>
        Rough distances:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>From Club Wyndham Grand Desert: about 10 to 12 minutes by rideshare.</li>
        <li>From the Arts District: about 5 to 7 minutes by rideshare.</li>
        <li>From Fremont Street: about a 3 to 4 minute rideshare, or a moderate walk when the weather is comfortable.</li>
        <li>From central Strip (Bellagio or Paris): about 15 to 18 minutes by rideshare.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Best timing relative to the itinerary</h3>
      <p>
        Option one:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>After the Arts District shopping on Day 2.</li>
        <li>Rideshare a short distance to the Neon Museum.</li>
        <li>Move from there back to the hotel to get ready for the O night.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Option two:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>On the Fremont and Old Vegas day, between Container Park and Fremont Street.</li>
        <li>You would go Container Park to Neon Museum to Fremont in one smooth loop.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Daytime versus nighttime</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Daytime: better for seeing details of each sign, and less dependence on weather when you have a tight show schedule.</li>
        <li>Nighttime: the signs that are wired light up and give you the classic neon glow experience.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="small">
        Most visits last 45 to 60 minutes for a self guided walk, or around 90 minutes if
        you add a guided or enhanced nighttime option.
      </p>
    </section>

